sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the creation of potentially malicious script and executable files in Windows startup folders, which is a common persistence technique used by threat actors.
These files (.ps1, .vbs, .js, .bat, etc.) are automatically executed when a user logs in, making the Startup folder an attractive target for attackers.
This technique is frequently observed in malvertising campaigns and malware distribution where attackers attempt to maintain long-term access to compromised systems.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems), Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel (Nextron Systems)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: System Disk And Volume Reconnaissance Via Wmic.EXE
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
An adversary might use WMI to discover information about the system, such as the volume name, size,
free space, and other disk information. This can be done using the 'wmic' command-line utility and has been
observed being used by threat actors such as Volt Typhoon.

match_context.values: @{Product=Microsoft\xae Windows\xae Operating System; CurrentDirectory=C:\Users\Bruno\Desktop\; OriginalFileName=wmic.exe; Hashes=MD5=A2EF3F0AD95FDA9262A5F9533B6DD1BD,SHA256=FA78C88DAC91FDF2EAC736E6900AC1EC4AB7A388B8F77A23FFA7E80A4AD29F5A,IMPHASH=D8770F1C24B7AAD7B5CD1817B3FEB2AA; Description=WMI Commandline Utility; FileVersion=10.0.19041.1 (WinBuild.160101.0800); ParentCommandLine=cmd.exe /c "wmic /node:. /namespace:'\\root\cimv2' path win32_logicaldisk get volumeserialnumber /format:list"; CommandLine=wmic  /node:. /namespace:'\\root\cimv2' path win32_logicaldisk get volumeserialnumber /format:list; EventID=1; ParentImage=C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe; IntegrityLevel=High; Image=C:\Windows\System32\wbem\WMIC.exe; Company=Microsoft Corporation}
